  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the difference between strong and eventual consistency? Give scenarios where each is appropriate.",
  "response_text": "The main difference between strong and eventual consistency lies in their guarantees for data integrity and transactional correctness.\n\nStrong Consistency:\n- Guarantees that all transactions will be executed atomically without any conflicts or inconsistencies.\n- Ensures that if two transactions attempt to modify the same piece of data simultaneously, only one can succeed.\n- Useful when dealing with large datasets or systems that need high availability and fault tolerance.\n\nEventual Consistency:\n- Guarantees that all transactions will eventually complete successfully, even if they encounter errors during execution.\n- Allows for partial updates or modifications to occur before the entire transaction is completed.\n- Suitable for systems that require some level of flexibility and allow for partial results.\n\nScenarios where Strong Consistency is Appropriate:\n- High availability and fault tolerance requirements in distributed systems.\n- Systems requiring atomicity and non-conflict resolution.\n- Applications that handle concurrent access to shared resources.\n\nScenarios where Eventual Consistency is Appropriate:\n- Systems that require partial updates or modifications to be processed before the entire transaction is committed.\n- Applications that tolerate partial results but want to ensure that no conflicting changes have been made.\n- Systems that prioritize overall system performance over strict atomicity guarantees.\n\nIn summary, Strong Consistency ensures absolute data integrity and transactional correctness, while Eventual Consistency allows for partial updates and partial results, making it suitable for various use cases depending on the specific needs of the application.",
